9d-a931-f546faf0473c?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa=
8-6m8ExkRNpU ], the ultimate platform for finance teams. Such big fans in f=
act, here=E2=80=99s a short list of the ways we=E2=80=99ve interreacted wit=
h them over the years:
Investors: Not Boring Capital has invested in two Ramp [ https://link.sbstc=
k.com/redirect/5504a0bd-7990-429d-a931-f546faf0473c?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.=
gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ] rounds
Analysts: Packy has written three deep dives on Ramp
Customers: Most importantly, we use Ramp at both Not Boring and Create. For=
 Create in particularly, Ramp is a very important partner.
You likely already know Ramp [ https://link.sbstck.com/redirect/5504a0bd-79=
90-429d-a931-f546faf0473c?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepK=
bqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ] has a cash back credit card, but what we really like (a=
nd use on a daily basis) is their Bill Pay and Flex products, which extend =
payment terms on all types of transactions. Its integrations and automation=
s also make closing the books easy each month.
We=E2=80=99re not alone, over 15,000 businesses (of all sizes) use Ramp. If=
 you want to join them and save 3.5% + close your books 8x faster, check th=
em out.
(1) DOE Finds Energy Jobs Have Increased in Nearly Every County in America =
[ https://link.sbstck.com/redirect/89f19d20-6da6-4fbc-a769-46f88e7d5863?j=
=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ]
From the Department of Energy
Energy employment is increasing in nearly every county across the United St=
ates. The number of energy jobs increased in 95% of American counties from =
2021 to 2022.
There goes that man again, Jobs Biden.
Seems like all of that investment in clean energy is translating into real =
jobs growth. The renewable energy sector is benefitting from decades of dec=
lining cost curves and pushes towards a clean energy transition, and it see=
ms that the Inflation Reduction Act is accelerating its deployment and job =
growth in the sector. The IRA has already dumped tens of billions of dollar=
s of investment into spurring the clean energy transition, and that=E2=80=
=99s translating to real jobs.=20
Sci-fi ideas [ https://link.sbstck.com/redirect/925b4b63-6247-410a-8e11-d0b=
36e450a02?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNp=
U ] are a third of the battle =E2=80=94 John Jacob Astor IV wrote about Roo=
ftop Windmills [ https://link.sbstck.com/redirect/aad1c177-4b94-4c83-a21a-7=
7963ca545e6?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkR=
NpU ] and Windmill Masts [ https://link.sbstck.com/redirect/2576cd2d-806c-4=
40f-a0a4-ac96754b6786?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOs=
a8-6m8ExkRNpU ] in 1894 and Hugo Gernsback imagined solar panels as Helio-D=
ynamophores [ https://link.sbstck.com/redirect/007ad602-a5ec-4426-a64f-5813=
8e124e14?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU=
 ] in 1911. Turning the ideas into working technology is another third. And=
 actually rolling out the technology is a final third. That part can and co=
ntinues to create new jobs =E2=80=94 over 170,000 new jobs in the last year=
 alone in the case of energy.=20
(2) Scientists Reconstructed a Pink Floyd Song From Brain Activity [ https:=
//link.sbstck.com/redirect/58efaca0-3e22-4f0b-abb0-1e080a300d0d?j=3DeyJ1Ijo=
iOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ]
Daniela Hernandez [ https://link.sbstck.com/redirect/450e19e2-9833-4b9b-844=
f-cfbedb946eb9?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8E=
xkRNpU ] for The Wall Street Journal
Neuroscientists at the University of California, Berkeley reconstructed Pin=
k Floyd=E2=80=99s classic rock song =E2=80=9CAnother Brick in the Wall, Par=
t 1=E2=80=9D using recordings of the brain activity of 29 patients who hear=
d the song while undergoing brain surgery. Though less polished than the ba=
nd=E2=80=99s version, the reconstructed tune was recognizable.
Last week, we covered that Nueralink (Elon=E2=80=99s Brain Computer Interfa=
ce company) had raised a $280M Series D to accelerate its products which he=
lp patients translate thoughts into physical movements. This week, a team o=
f researchers have gotten one step closer to developing devices that transl=
ate brain activity into sound.
Essentially, the device reads brain activity and translates those signals i=
nto spoken word or other sounds. You should check out the side-by-side comp=
arison of the song and the brain output in the WSJ article [ https://link.s=
bstck.com/redirect/58efaca0-3e22-4f0b-abb0-1e080a300d0d?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3Q=
ifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ]. Such a device would be t=
ransformative for people that can=E2=80=99t speak.=20
But since we=E2=80=99ve been on the Sci-Fi train here recently, let=E2=80=
=99s take it a step further. Imagine a device that could automatically tran=
slate your thoughts into any language, automatically making you a polyglot.=
 Or attaching the device to a baby, translating the brain signals behind ni=
ghttime cries into well-articulated statements of need. Or better yet, how =
about hooking up one of these devices to your pooch=E2=80=A6oh if the dogs =
could talk=E2=80=A6
That=E2=80=99s a ways away, but in the meantime, as is the case with most o=
f these cutting edge brain-technologies, people truly in need will be the f=
irst to benefit.=20
(3) Pig Kidneys Performing Effectively in Two Brain-Dead Patients [ https:/=
/link.sbstck.com/redirect/2cdd70c4-d2d7-4405-b9ec-7c0bc19773f4?j=3DeyJ1Ijoi=
OXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ]  [ https://link.sb=
stck.com/redirect/2cdd70c4-d2d7-4405-b9ec-7c0bc19773f4?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3Qi=
fQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ]
Roni Caryn Rabin [ https://link.sbstck.com/redirect/8939ba6a-cfce-402e-b40e=
-13dcde48fdc3?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8Ex=
kRNpU ] for The New York Times
A number of studies last year demonstrated that pig kidneys that had been t=
ransplanted into brain-dead individuals made urine, an essential function, =
for short periods of time. But the U.A.B. study is the first to clearly sho=
w that the organs also filter creatinine, a byproduct of muscle contraction=
s that must be removed from the blood.
Thousands of people die each year waiting for kidney transplants. There=E2=
=80=99s about a 100,000 person waitlist for kidney transplants in the U.S. =
each year, but only 25,000 transplants are performed due to a shortage of h=
uman organ donors. That=E2=80=99s where the pigs come in!
New research, produced by two separate teams, demonstrates functional pig k=
idneys in brain-dead human patients. Previous experiments have show that pi=
g-kidneys can make urine, but this new research shows that pig kidneys are =
also effective at filtering creatinine from the body. (As an aside, creatin=
ine =E2=89=A0 creatine. Creatinine is the waste product creatine. If your k=
idneys are functioning properly, taking creatine will not harmfully increas=
e creatinine levels.)
The ability to safely and effectively use animal organs in humans would, of=
 course, limit the shortage organs needed for transplants. We=E2=80=99re st=
ill a bit of a ways off: the experiments have only occurred in two brain-de=
ad patients, but the teams are seeking FDA approval for a clinical trial in=
 live patients.
Pigs are becoming humans. Or maybe, humans are becoming pigs. I=E2=80=99m n=
ot sure how the logic works there. But whether or not I should eat bacon is=
 about to become a much more morally complex question=E2=80=A6
(4) Unitree teases new H1 humanoid robot [ https://link.sbstck.com/redirect=
/9913f639-a04e-4214-a6fa-caeb601c3d59?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlN=
uaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ]
Mike Oitzman [ https://link.sbstck.com/redirect/c387e356-399c-4459-9443-490=
0d72c6027?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNp=
U ] for The Robot Report
If science keeps progressing, the first step is we all become human pig hyb=
rids. The next step is that we=E2=80=99re replaced by robot humanoids all t=
ogether.
The race to commercialize humanoid robots is heating up. There=E2=80=99s do=
zens of companies competing to develop and sell a useful human-like robot, =
and now, some of the prototypes are quite good. One of those companies, Uni=
tree, introduced its general purpose humanoid robot, called H1, this week. =
The robot, which walks like a human that needs to find a toilet really badl=
y, is expected to be available for sale in the next =E2=80=9C3-10 years=E2=
=80=9D (bit of breathing room there for the team) for under $90,000.
These humanoid robots could perform a range of tasks, from warehouse workin=
g to caregiving, to soldiering, and free up time for us pighumans to focus =
on more worthwhile projects.=20
(5) Coinbase Financial Markets, Inc. secures approval to bring federally re=
gulated crypto futures trading to eligible US customers [ https://link.sbst=
ck.com/redirect/7c4a1ce2-507f-463c-89dd-bb84f5f390ee?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ=
=2Egb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ]
From Coinbase
Coinbase will now be the first crypto-native leader to directly offer tradi=
tional spot crypto trading alongside regulated and leveraged crypto futures=
, on an integrated trading solution for our verified customers.
The ability to trade leveraged crypto futures isn=E2=80=99t necessarily cau=
se for optimism in and of itself, but we=E2=80=99re highlighting this story=
 because it=E2=80=99s a big W for Coinbase in its ongoing fight to bring re=
gulatory clarity to the industry.=20
Coinbase has long held that if the SEC offered a path to register, they=E2=
=80=99d take it. The registration as a Futures Commission Merchant with the=
 CFTC shows that they=E2=80=99re serious, and the CFTC=E2=80=99s willingnes=
s to work with Coinbase highlights a sane approach to regulation.=20
And as of last night, reports are that the SEC will greenlight Ether-Future=
s ETFs [ https://link.sbstck.com/redirect/4f360687-a095-4601-bddb-808c284f8=
b85?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ].=
=20
Coinbase has stood strong and it=E2=80=99s starting to get results, for its=
elf and the industry. Props to the company and its CEO Brian Armstrong for =
fighting the good fight.=20
Crypto is here to stay. Even if you=E2=80=99re a crypto skeptic, it makes v=
ery little sense to have regulatory bodies driving the industry outside of =
the U.S. Even if you think there=E2=80=99s just a small chance of crypto be=
coming a major part of the economy in the future, there=E2=80=99s high expe=
cted value of having it centered in U.S. Moves like this make it more likel=
y that that will be the case. A government that isn=E2=80=99t anti-innovati=
on is good for the country.=20
Plus, how can you not love a company that=E2=80=99s waging a serious legal =
battle against the US Government while also bringing beautiful art like Sum=
mer Kevin into the world?
Bonus: American Dynamo [ https://link.sbstck.com/redirect/9e5b7261-2b80-435=
b-98ad-3689503ada6d?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8=
-6m8ExkRNpU ]
From The Information
=E2=80=9CTen years ago, if you had said, =E2=80=98We want to invest in gove=
rnment companies,=E2=80=99 you would have been laughed out of the room,=E2=
=80=9D she said in her opening speech [ https://link.sbstck.com/redirect/57=
7d613d-fa86-42cb-ba95-35e2ba3b5e22?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaM=
ZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ]. She pointed to the skyrocketing valuations of=
 Anduril, SpaceX and Palantir as proof the doubters were wrong. =E2=80=9CTh=
is is why we=E2=80=99re introducing American dynamism, which we truly belie=
ve is a new category of innovation for Silicon Valley, for Washington and f=
or our country.=E2=80=9D
Packy here. Many of the companies we write about both here in the Weekly Do=
se and in Not Boring fall under the category that a16z=E2=80=99s Katherine =
Boyle dubbed =E2=80=9CAmerican Dynamism.=E2=80=9D In the post introducing t=
he firm=E2=80=99s AD practice, she wrote:
I call this American dynamism: it=E2=80=99s the recognition that seemingly =
insurmountable problems in our society =E2=80=94 from national security and=
 public safety to housing and education =E2=80=94 demand solutions that are=
n=E2=80=99t simply incremental changes that perpetuate the status quo. Thes=
e problems demand solutions from builders =E2=80=94 and it=E2=80=99s never =
been more vital that startups tackle these serious American problems.
When Katherine started investing in and promoting companies tackling seriou=
s American problems, it was unpopular at best. Just a few years and one Rus=
sian invasion later, the industry has caught up.=20
This profile on Katherine by The Information=E2=80=99s Margaux MacColl is w=
orth a weekend read. It=E2=80=99s a good example of being non-consensus and=
 right, and of working towards something you believe in even when others do=
n=E2=80=99t believe.=20
That=E2=80=99s all for this week. We=E2=80=99ll be back in your inbox on Tu=
esday.
Thanks for reading,
Dan + Packy

